7th February¶

Binning¶

Because audio event files can be different lengths, with a variety of ranges of frequencies, it can be very difficult to feed this raw signal component data into a neural network, as we would need to build in an ability to tackle dynamic ranges of data. Instead, we will bin the frequencies into set frequency bins.

In [6]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import os
from tqdm import tqdm
%matplotlib notebook

let's read in our data, now fourier-transformed and filtered. As an artifact of saving it as a dataframe earlier, we need to drop a residual auto-index column.

In [3]:
manual_dataframe = pd.read_csv("E:/data/DATA/ASCII/AllData/headless_only/TimeseriesAndAmplitude/FFT_dB/20110829.002440.YW.NAB1.HHE.csv")
manual_dataframe.drop(["Unnamed: 0"], axis=1, inplace=True)

As discussed before, we cannot find any signals above half our sampling rate, Given our 0.01 second sample interval, that gives us a Niquist limit of $$\frac{1\ sample\ period}{0.01 seconds} = 100Hz\ sampling\ frequency = 50Hz\ ceiling$$

This leaves us with data in the region of 0 $\leq$ 50 Hz. We will use evenly spaced bins, of no more than 1Hz in width.

Now, we need to just add a few vital pieces of information to the binned data:

  • The whole-event mean
  • The whole-event median

And most vitally:

  • The label

The label is what will tell Tensorflow if this is an event or not, and as we are running a binary classification experiment the value is either 1 (is an event) or 0 (is not an event). We will also add the name of the event - which we are adding manually for now but we will automate later - which will serve as the Primary Key.

Now we need to automate this for the rest of the events, and append them to the attributes_dataframe.

Automation¶

Let's summarise our steps above into a function, like we have before.

In [52]:
file_list = os.listdir("../../../DATA/ASCII/AllData/headless_only/TimeseriesAndAmplitude/FFT_dB/")[1:]
#skipping the first item in the list which we have already processed

primary_key_name = map(lambda x: x[:-4], file_list)

filepath_list = map(lambda x: "../../../DATA/ASCII/AllData/headless_only/TimeseriesAndAmplitude/FFT_dB/" + x, file_list)

def fft_to_attribute(input_filepath, event_code, output_dataframe, no_of_bins, is_event_boolean):
    break_points = np.linspace(0, 50, no_of_bins+1)
    input_dataframe = pd.read_csv(input_filepath)
    input_dataframe.drop(["Unnamed: 0"], axis=1, inplace=True)
    input_dataframe['bins']=pd.cut(input_dataframe["Sampling_Frequencies"],break_points, right=False)

    whole_event_mean = input_dataframe['Decibels'].mean()
    whole_event_median = input_dataframe['Decibels'].median()
    origin_filename = event_code
    stats_and_labels_dict = {'Mean': whole_event_mean,
                         'Median': whole_event_median,
                         'Label': is_event_boolean}

    intermediary_dataseries = input_dataframe.groupby("bins")["Decibels"].mean()
    
    stats_and_labels_series = pd.Series(data=stats_and_labels_dict)
    intermediary_dataseries = pd.concat([stats_and_labels_series, intermediary_dataseries])

    intermediary_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(data=intermediary_dataseries, columns=[origin_filename])
    intermediary_dataframe = intermediary_dataframe.transpose()
    return pd.concat([output_dataframe, intermediary_dataframe])
